\begin_layout Standard
The possibility of realizing topological superfluids and manipulating Majorana
 fermions in solid-state and ultracold atomic systems is currently a topic
 of great theoretical and experimental interest 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hasan2010,Qi2011"

\end_inset

, due to their potential applications in fault-tolerant topological quantum
 computation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nayak2008"

\end_inset

.
 Roughly, Majorana fermions constitute 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

half
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of an ordinary Dirac fermion, in the sense that two real Majorana fermions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 - which can be separated in arbitrary distance - mathematically define
 a complex fermion operator 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\gamma_{1}+i\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wilczek2009"

\end_inset

.
 The exchange statistics of Majorana fermions is exotic.
 Unlike conventional bosons and fermions, braiding Majorana fermions around
 one another in a 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{N}$
\end_inset

-dimensional Hilbert space (spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 well-separated Majorana fermions) produce non-Abelian unitary transformations
 in the Hilbert space.
 Quantum information can then be non-locally encoded in the Hilbert space
 by such braiding operators and be immune to decoherence, which is ideal
 for the purpose of quantum computation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nayak2008"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At present, a number of experimental setting have been suggested for hosting
 Majorana fermions under appropriate conditions, including chiral 
\shape italic
p
\shape default
-wave superconductors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Read2000"

\end_inset

, fractional quantum Hall systems at filling 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=5/2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Moore1991"

\end_inset

, and topological insulators or semiconductor nanowires in proximity to
 an 
\shape italic
s
\shape default
-wave superconductor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fu2008,Sau2010,Oreg2010"

\end_inset

.
 The latest setting, which seems to be the most practical setup, is described
 by the Sau-Lutchyn-Tewari-Das Sarma (SLTD) model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sau2010"

\end_inset

.
 The key idea of this mechanism is that the Fermi surfaces are spin-split
 by a Rashba spin-orbit coupling and an out-of-plane Zeeman field.
 If the number of particles is tuned to make the inner Fermi surface disappearin
g, the superconductivity will be only induced by pairing on the outer Fermi
 surface, which is of 
\shape italic
p
\shape default
-wave in nature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zhang2008,Sato2009"

\end_inset

, and therefore becomes topologically nontrivial.
 Following this promising theoretical model, exciting experimental progress
 for the observation of Majorana fermions has been made very recently 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mourik2012,Williams2012,Rokhinson2012"

\end_inset

, although unambiguous confirmation for their existence still remains elusive.
