\begin_layout Standard
The SLTD mechanism uses an out-of-plane Zeeman field to split the Fermi
 surfaces 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sau2010"

\end_inset

.
 It is interesting that such a splitting can also be achieved by applying
 a large in-plane
\emph on
 
\emph default
Zeeman field in combination with spin-orbit coupling, as illustrated in
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig1"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the in-plane field together with spin-orbit coupling is known
 to introduce an asymmetry in the single-particle dispersion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dong2013PRA,Shenoy2013"

\end_inset

, consequently to induce Cooper pairs with nonzero centre-of-mass momentum
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zheng2013,Wu2013,Liu2013,Dong2013NJP,Hu2013,Qu2013,Zhang2013"

\end_inset

 and hence realize the so-called spatially inhomogeneous Fulde-Ferrell (FF)
 pairing scenario 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fulde1964"

\end_inset

.
 It is therefore of interest to ask whether a topological phase transition
 can also be driven by an in-plane Zeeman field only? If the answer is yes,
 then we must be able to observe an exotic inhomogeneous topological FF
 superfluid that supports Majorana fermions.
 The understanding of such a new-type topological state of matter may greatly
 enhance our knowledge of topological superfluidity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this Letter, we examine the new mechanism by using an ultracold atomic
 setting of a three-dimensional (3D) spin-orbit coupled atomic Fermi gas
 subject to an in-plane Zeeman field.
 By increasing the field strength above a threshold, we observe the change
 of the topology of the Fermi surfaces that triggers a topological phase
 transition.
 The resulting inhomogeneous topological FF superfluid is gapless in the
 bulk with nodal points form closed surfaces in momentum space.
 While in real space, it hosts unidirected Majorana surface states that
 propagate in the same direction on opposite boundaries.
 These unique features are absent in standard topological superfluids known
 so far such as the 
\shape italic
p
\shape default
-wave superconductors or the SLTD-type superconductors, both of which are
 gapped in the bulk and support counter-propagating Majorana modes at surfaces.
 We find that the phase space for the proposed novel gapless topological
 FF superfluid is significant, implying that it could be easily realized
 in current ultracold atomic experiments owing to the unprecedented tunability
 of synthetic spin-orbit coupling, Zeeman field and interatomic interaction
 in cold-atom laboratory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lin2011,Wang2012,Cheuk2012"

\end_inset

.
 We also discuss briefly the potential implementation of our proposal in
 solid-state setups.
\end_layout

