\begin_layout Standard
Physically, the transition to a gapless phase can be well characterized
 by a global energy gap 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{g}=\min E_{2+}(\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

, which is the half of the energy difference between the minimum energy
 of the particle branch and the maximum of the hole branch due to the particle-h
ole symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2+}(\mathbf{k})=-E_{2-}(-\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{g}\leq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{g}>0$
\end_inset

 characterize a gapless and gapped state, respectively.
 The topological phase transition, on the contrary, is related to the change
 of the topology of the Fermi surfaces.
 It is well known that such a change must be accompanied with the close
 and re-open of an energy gap at some specific points in momentum space
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hasan2010,Qi2011"

\end_inset

.
 In our continuum case of a homogeneous Fermi gas, this occurs precisely
 at the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig3"

\end_inset

b).
 Therefore, naïvely the topological transition can be determined from the
 condition 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2+}(\mathbf{k}=\mathbf{0})=0$
\end_inset

 or more explicitly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h_{c2}=\sqrt{\left(\mu-\frac{\hbar^{2}q^{2}}{8m}\right)^{2}+\Delta^{2}}-\frac{\lambda q}{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the absence of a FF pairing momentum (
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

), the above condition reduces to the well-known criterion 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $h_{c}=\sqrt{\mu^{2}+\Delta^{2}}$
\end_inset

 for the appearance of a SLTD topological superfluid when an out-of-plane
 Zeeman field is applied 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sau2010,Oreg2010"

\end_inset

.
 It is interesting that the gapless transition always occurs before the
 topological transition, as a result of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{g}\leq E_{2+}(\mathbf{k}=\mathbf{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, bulk-gapped
\emph on
 
\emph default
topological FF superfluids, if exist, must appear at very high in-plane
 Zeeman field.
 As a superfluid analogue of strong 3D topological insulators 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hasan2010,Qi2011"

\end_inset

, they are anticipated to have the unique feature of a single Dirac cone
 for the energy dispersion of the Majorana edge states.
